# Operating Doctrine

Apply these to every task, regardless of domain.

## Research first
- Before implementing, inspect existing code: components, utilities, hooks, data-fetching patterns, configs, and tests. Reuse over rebuild.
- For large or ambiguous tasks, produce a short plan (scope, files to touch, tests) before writing code.

## Verify before claiming done
- Never report success without running it. Run typecheck, lint, and the relevant tests; fix and re-run until green.
- Add or update tests for the behavior you changed.

## Review every change
- After generating code, do a focused review pass: correctness, edge cases, security, and style. Flag issues with severity (critical / suggestion / nice-to-have).
- Keep diffs small and reviewable; stop and reassess if a change is drifting from intent.

## Iterate and improve the kit
- Start simple; add or refine rules and skills only when a repeated pattern or mistake emerges. Avoid over-engineering early.
- After a significant session, run a retro and propose concrete edits to these rules and skills.

## Security posture
- Layered security: combine LLM review with deterministic SAST tools and human oversight; never rely on one alone.
- Treat skills, hooks, and MCP servers as managed dependencies - know their source and trust level.
- Never commit secrets. Parameterize inputs. Validate and sanitize external data.

## Human oversight
- Surface risky or irreversible actions (migrations, deletes, deploys, force-push) for confirmation rather than proceeding silently.
